There is a shocking contrast between the way alcohol has been advertised and sold to us and the true impact it has on the brain and body.

In Episode 51 of the Sun & Moon Sober Living Podcast, @JamesSwanwick explains why he calls alcohol “attractively packaged poison” and why everyone could benefit from cutting back or eliminating it completely.

We discuss:

✨ How and why James quit drinking
✨ Developing confidence to socialize sober
✨ The clever marketing of “Attractively Packaged Poison”
✨ The role of cultural conditioning
✨ The impact of alcohol on the workplace (i.e. career growth, productivity, revenue, etc.)
✨ Inspiring success stories
✨ Practical tips for quitting drinking

James Swanwick is an Australian-American investor, entrepreneur, speaker and former SportsCenter anchor on ESPN. He is the creator of the Alcohol Free Lifestyle, which helps people change their relationship to alcohol; the host of the podcast, “Alcohol Free Lifestyle”, creator of “Project 90”, which helps high achievers get lifetime power over alcohol, and creator of blue-light blocking glasses Swannies by Swanwick Sleep, which improve your sleep.

Environmental factors, as well as gene and environment interactions, account for the remainder of the risk

This explains why a drunken idea doesn't usually seem great the morning after. ⁠

Alcohol increases the inhibitory neurotransmitter, GABA, which normally reduces energy levels. This slows your thought, speech, and movements as you drink more.⁠

Alcohol is tricking your brain!⁠
⁠
Alcohol jacks up dopamine levels in your brain’s reward center. You experience the same pleasure as hanging out with friends, going on vacation, getting a big bonus at work, and taking certain substances.⁠
⁠
This tricks you into thinking that alcohol makes you feel great. So you keep drinking to get more dopamine release. ⁠
⁠
Over time, with more drinking, the dopamine effect diminishes until it’s almost non-existent. ⁠
⁠
That’s why many excessive drinkers say drinking eventually stopped working. They no longer got the euphoria from drinking. ⁠
⁠
That’s why drinking is addictive. You’re chasing euphoria. And when you quit drinking, it takes the brain some time to begin naturally producing dopamine again⁠

Are you an entrepreneur?

If so, I invite you to do a quick calculation to determine what your drinking habits are costing your business financially.

(I acknowledge people’s motivation for quitting drinking is often has little to do with money. Nevertheless, doing this calculation may be eye-opening for you enough to finally spur you into action to do something about your drinking habits)

Let’s forget, for a second, the amount of money you spend on alcohol and alcohol-related activities. 

Instead, let’s just focus on the amount of money you DON’T generate because of your drinking.

Here’s your 3-step calculator:

1-> With your drinking habit the way it is, how much revenue did you generate in your business last year?

2 -> If you were alcohol-free and enjoyed a clearer mind, more energy, less stress, extra motivation & laser focus, how much revenue could you generate this year?

3 -> Subtract (1) from (2)

Whatever (3) is, that’s what your drinking costs you in lost revenue each year. 

That’s your ALRC number. (Alcohol Lost Revenue Calculator).

What’s your number?

Look at it. 

Think about it. 

Every time you drink, that’s what it’s costing you in lost revenue. 

That’s money you’re NOT generating.

You’re leaving it on the table. 

Again, I know it’s not always about the money.

Maybe you want better health, relationships and happiness.

But nevertheless, lost money in your business is a barometer of what drinking may be costing you.

I squandered money for years when I drank, only to generate millions in revenue when I quit. 

I currently own two, seven-figure businesses and a third, six-figure business.

When you’re clear in mind, you make better decisions. 

You make an extra cold call. 

You try an additional marketing effort. 

You do an additional deal. 

These things all make you money. 

And by the way, your ALRC number doesn’t even include the money you actually spend on alcohol. 

Is continuing to drink worth what it costs you?

If you quit, you can generate (3).

If you continue drinking, you won’t generate (3). 

That’s the reality. 

Multiply (3) by five and you can see what your drinking may cost you over the next five years.
